  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[t]]></fr:tex> be a closed point of the generic fibre of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T']]></fr:tex> be its closure in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
      There exists a dense Zariski open <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T=p^{-1}(U)\cap  T']]></fr:tex> is an étale covering of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[U]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

    <fr:p>We lose no generality by assuming that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s\in  T]]></fr:tex>.
      In the diagram
      
  <fr:embedded-tex hash="41d7cc0caa328a65942710d85f8bc792"><fr:embedded-tex-preamble><![CDATA[
    \usepackage {amsmath}
    \usepackage {amssymb}
    \usepackage {tikz-cd}
  ]]></fr:embedded-tex-preamble><fr:embedded-tex-body><![CDATA[\begin {tikzcd}
        \pi _1(T,s)
          \ar [r]
          \ar [d,swap,"a"]
        & \pi _1(S,s)
          \ar [d,"c"]
      \\\pi _1(U,p(s))
        \ar [r,swap,"b"]
        & \pi _1(M,p(s))
      \end {tikzcd}]]></fr:embedded-tex-body></fr:embedded-tex>

      the image of the arrow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> is of finite index, since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[T]]></fr:tex> is a finite étale covering, and the arrow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[b]]></fr:tex> is surjective, since <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[M\setminus  U]]></fr:tex> is of real codimension <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\geqslant 2]]></fr:tex>.
      The image of the arrow <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[c]]></fr:tex> is thus of finite index.</fr:p>
  </fr:mainmatter>
